{"title_page": "Kweilin incident", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Kweilin'' incident}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = \n| occurrence_type =  Incident\n| image = Douglas DC-2.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| alt = \n| caption = A DC-2 passenger airliner\n| date = {{start date|1938|08|24}}\n| summary = Strafing on the ground\n| site = [[Zhongshan]], [[Guangdong]], China<ref name=sina/>\n| coordinates =  {{coord|22.517|N|113.393|E|type:adm2nd_region:CN-44_source:Gaode|format=dms|display=it}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Douglas DC-2]]\n| aircraft_name = ''Kweilin''\n| operator = [[China National Aviation Corporation]]\n| tail_number = 32\n| origin = [[Hong Kong]]\n| stopover = \n| stopover0 = [[Wuchow]]\n| stopover1 = [[Chungking]]\n| stopover2 = \n| stopover3 = \n| last_stopover = \n| destination = [[Chengtu]]\n| passengers = 14\n| crew = 3\n| injuries = 1\n| fatalities =14 \n| missing =\n| survivors = 3\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|s=\u6842\u6797\u53f7\u4e8b\u4ef6\n|t=\u6842\u6797\u865f\u4e8b\u4ef6\n|p=Gu\u00ecl\u00edn h\u00e0o sh\u00ecji\u00e0n\n|w=Kuei-lin hao shih-chien\n|j=gwai3 lam4 hou6 si6 gin6*2\n}}\n\nThe '''''Kweilin'' incident''' occurred on August 24, 1938 when a [[Douglas DC-2]] airliner (the ''Kweilin'') carrying 18 passengers and crew was destroyed by Japanese aircraft in China. There were fourteen fatalities. It was the [[List of airliner shootdown incidents|first civilian airliner in history to be shot down]] by hostile aircraft.<ref name=crouchp158>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA158 158]. Quote: \"No civilian airliner in history had ever been shot down by hostile air action.\"</ref> The pilot was American and the crew and passengers Chinese. As it was unprecedented for a civilian aircraft to be attacked, there was international diplomatic outrage over the incident. In the United States, it helped solidify the popular view that Japan was morally wrong in [[Second Sino-Japanese War|their war against China]],<ref name=crouchp168>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA168 168]. Quote: \"Fifteen months of blatant aggression had evaporated whatever goodwill most Americans felt toward Japan. It had become obvious which side held the moral high ground, and why, and although the overwhelming majority of Americans had absolutely no interest in fighting for China, if a few of their compatriots were willing, the average citizen was quite prepared to allow them to do so.\"</ref> but the incident was not enough to spur the US into action against Japan despite Chinese entreaties.<ref name=crouchp167>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA167 167]. Quote: \"in relating the shoot-down and Madame Sun's address, an editorial in Hong Kong's ''South China Morning Post'' noted that:\n:one of these days, the Great Democracies may find out that there is something, after all, for which no price can be fixed, they may learn that the only proper and wise way to deal with the aggressors is to demand an eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth. In short, there will be a time when the peace-loving nations will be compelled to meet force by force. Until then, nothing can check Japan from her career of truculent destruction.\"</ref> The ''Kweilin'' was re-built, and destroyed by the Japanese a second time two years later.\n\n==''Kweilin'' Incident==\n\nDC-2 number 32 ''Kweilin''{{#tag:ref|''Kweilin'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u6842\u6797\u865f|s=\u6842\u6797\u53f7|p=Gu\u00ecl\u00edn-h\u00e0o|w=Kuei-lin hao|labels=no}}|group=note}} was owned by [[China National Aviation Corporation]] (CNAC), one of the first commercial airlines in China. It was operated under contract by [[Pan American World Airways|Pan American]] pilots and management who were mostly American in 1938.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnac.org/pilots01.htm |title=CNAC pilots |website=CNAC.org |author= |date= |accessdate=August 28, 2014}}</ref> The plane was on a routine civilian passenger flight from the British colony of Hong Kong to [[Wuchow]], the first stop en route to [[Chungking]]<!--historical names--> and [[Chengtu]] in [[Szechwan]] province. From Hong Kong, Chengtu was over {{convert|750|miles|km|-1}} to the northwest. The flight had fourteen passengers, plus a steward,<ref name=crouchp156>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA156 156]</ref> radio operator Joe Loh,{{#tag:ref|''Joe Loh'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u7f85\u662d\u660e|s=\u7f57\u662d\u660e|p=Lu\u00f3 Zh\u0101om\u00edng|w=Lo Chao-ming|labels=no}}|group=note}} copilot Lieu Chung-chuan,{{#tag:ref|''Lieu Chung-chuan'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u5289\u5d07\u4f7a|s=\u5218\u5d07\u4f7a|p=Li\u00fa Ch\u00f3ngqu\u00e1n|w=Liu Ch'ung-ch'\u00fcan|labels=no}}|group=note}} and American pilot Hugh Leslie Woods.<ref name=crouchp155>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA155 155]</ref>\n\nThe ''Kweilin'' left Hong Kong at 8:04am.<ref name=crouchp155/> At 8:30am, soon after entering Chinese airspace, Woods spotted eight Japanese pontoon-fitted planes in what he believed to be an attacking formation. Woods took evasive maneuvers by circling into a cloud bank and was fired upon by the Japanese planes, their intentions made clear. As the DC-2 was unarmed, Woods put it into a fast dive to find a place to make an emergency landing, but the fields were [[rice paddies]] crisscrossed with dikes. Woods saw a river and made a perfect water landing with no injuries or damage; the plane was designed to float. However, Woods soon discovered he was the only person aboard who knew how to swim and the swift current bore the plane into full view of the circling Japanese planes.<ref name=crouchp157b>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA157 157]. <!-- Quote: \"The passengers could leap and strike out for safety, but none moved. They stared at Woody with drawn faces, eyes blank with fear. ''Jesus Christ'', he realized, ''they can't swim!''\" --></ref> They began to strafe it with machine gun fire. Woods saw an unused boat on shore and swam to retrieve it. During the swim he was repeatedly strafed with machine gun fire but was not hit.<ref name=crouchp157>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA157 157]</ref> On reaching shore, he saw the plane had drifted far down river and was so riddled with bullets it was sinking with only the tail and wing still visible. After about an hour of continuous attacks the Japanese planes left.<ref name=crouchp158/> The survivors were Woods, the radio operator Joe Loh and a wounded passenger, Lou Zhaonian.{{#tag:ref|''Lou Zhaonian'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u6a13\u5146\u5ff5|s=\u697c\u5146\u5ff5|p=L\u00f3u Zh\u00e0oni\u00e0n|w=Lou Chao-nien|labels=no}} - also stated as \"C. N. Lou\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,760078,00.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826100544/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,760078,00.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-08-26|title=War in China: By Mistake|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=1938-09-05|accessdate=2018-09-12}}</ref>|group=note}} The dead included two women, a five-year-old boy and a baby. One victim had been hit thirteen times.<ref name=crouchp165>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA165 165]</ref>\n\n==Cause and effects==\n[[File:Hu Yun.jpg|thumb|upright|Hu Yun, Chairman of the [[Bank of Communications]] (pictured in ''{{ill|Who's Who in China|zh|\u4e2d\u56fd\u540d\u4eba\u5f55}}'', was killed in the incident]]\nIt was speculated that the reason for the attack was to assassinate Chinese President [[Sun Yat-sen]]'s only son, [[Sun Fo]], who was expected to be on the ''Kweilin''.<ref name=crouchp164>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA164 164]</ref> In fact Sun Fo had taken an earlier flight that day with a different airline, [[Eurasia Aviation Corporation|Eurasia]]. Sun Fo later claimed a secretary had made a mistake and had publicly announced the wrong flight. It was speculated that Sun Fo intentionally announced his departure on the wrong plane, in effect sacrificing the ''Kweilin'' so that his real flight could travel unmolested.<ref name=crouchp165/> While the Japanese government never officially acknowledged why or if they attacked the ''Kweilin'', they said henceforth that while they took care they would not accept responsibility for civilian aircraft flying in a war zone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E04E1DC1E38EE3ABC4E51DFBE668383629EDE |title=Japan Bars Pledge on Civilian Planes |work=[[New York Times]] |author=Hallett Abend |date=August 26, 1938 |accessdate=August 31, 2014}}</ref><ref name=fg1sep38>{{citation |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1938/1938%20-%202454.html |journal=Flight |date=1 September 1938 |title=The China National Affair |page=184}}</ref> The Japanese Foreign Office claimed not to have fired on the aircraft but to have chased it as it was behaving suspiciously.<ref name=fg1sep38/> A Japanese-language newspaper, ''The Hong Kong Nippo'', admitted that although Sun Fo was the object of the attack, \"our wild eagles intended to capture [him] alive.\"<ref name=\"crouchp166b\">Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA166 166]. <!-- Quote: \"In Tokyo, Rear Admiral Kiyoshi Noda denied the navy fliers attacked with the deliberate intention of assassinating Sun Fo, but the most spectacular quibble appeared in a Japanese-language daily called ''The Hong Kong Nippo'', which admitted that although Sun Fo was the object of the attack, \u201cour wild eagles intended to capture [him] alive.\u201d\"--></ref>\n\n[[File:Xu Xinliu.jpg|thumb|left|upright|{{ill|Singloh Hsu|zh|\u5f90\u65b0\u516d}} (Xu Xinliu), General Manager of [[The National Commercial Bank]], pictured in ''Who's Who in China}}'', was killed in the incident]]\nThree prominent Chinese bankers were among the passengers killed in the incident. They were Hu Yun,{{#tag:ref|''Hu Yun'': {{zh|c=\u80e1\u7b60|p=H\u00fa Y\u00fan|w=Hu Y\u00fcn|labels=no}}|group=note}} Chairman of the [[Bank of Communications]], {{ill|Singloh Hsu|zh|\u5f90\u65b0\u516d}},{{#tag:ref|''Singloh Hsu'': {{zh|c=\u5f90\u65b0\u516d|p=X\u00fa X\u012bnli\u00f9|w=Hs\u00fc Hsin-liu|labels=no}}|group=note}} General Manager of [[The National Commercial Bank]], and Wang Yumei,{{#tag:ref|''Wang Yumei'': {{zh|c=\u738b\u5b87\u6963|p=W\u00e1ng Y\u01d4m\u00e9i|w=Wang Y\u00fc-mei|labels=no}}|group=note}} an executive of the [[Central Bank of the Republic of China]]. Their deaths were a significant loss to the Chinese banking industry.<ref name=sina>{{cite web|author=Hu Zhuoran (\u80e1\u5353\u7136) |script-title=zh:\u4fb5\u534e\u65e5\u519b\u66fe\u51fb\u843d\u4e2d\u56fd\u6c11\u822a\u5ba2\u673a |trans-title=Japanese invading forces shot down a Chinese civilian aircraft |url=http://history.sina.com.cn/his/zl/2014-07-18/112995625.shtml |publisher=[[Sina (company)|Sina]] |language=Chinese |date=July 18, 2014 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6S9qPEOni?url=http://history.sina.com.cn/his/zl/2014-07-18/112995625.shtml |archive-date=28 August 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe incident was widely reported, due, in part, to its novelty as the first time a civilian airliner had ever been brought down by hostile aircraft.<ref name=crouchp158/> A popular newsreel, titled ''Kweilin Tragedy'', showed to sell-out crowds for weeks in Hong Kong.<ref name=crouch166/> It had an interview with Woods and showed the \"mutilated airplane, scattered mail bags, and bullet-riddled corpses.\"<ref name=\"crouch166\">Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA166 166].<!-- Quote: \"Film producers compiled a newsreel about the \u201cKweilin Tragedy\u201d using film taken at the salvage site showing the mutilated airplane, scattered mail bags, and bullet-riddled corpses. Hugh Woods commentated, and it showed to packed houses in Hong Kong\u2019s Queens, Alhambra, and Central theaters on the first three days of September. The extreme demand resulted in the addition of two more dates the following week\" --></ref> After the incident, CNAC and other carriers began making night flights over China, using a new technology developed in Germany, \"[[Lorenz beam|Lorenz]]\", that allowed pilots to follow an auditory radio homing-beacon to the destination.<ref name=\"crouch169\">Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA169 169].<!-- Quote: \"Eurasia's chief pilot trained Chuck Sharp [of CNAC] to use Telefunken direction finders, an instantly responsive German system that allowed pilots to land at night or in bad weather. Using it, the pilot wore a headset that gave a null tone when he was \u201con the beam,\u201d flying directly toward the homing station. If the pilot deviated, the headset repeated either the Morse code letter \u201cA,\u201d ''dit dah, dit dah, dit dah, dit dah'', or \u201cN,\u201d ''dah dit, dah dit, dah dit'', to indicate needed left-right course corrections. Sharp was soon teaching CNAC's other pilots.\"--></ref> There was diplomatic outrage over the incident. In the United States, it helped solidify the popular view the Japan was morally wrong in the war against China,<ref name=crouchp168/> but the incident was not enough to spur the US into action against Japan despite Chinese entreaties.<ref name=crouchp167/>\n\nOn 6 September an aircraft of the Sino-German Eurasian Aviation Company was attacked near [[Liuchow]] by Japanese fighters while flying from Hong Kong to [[Yunnan]]. The company had already stopped flights to [[Hankow]] after the Kweilin attack.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1938/1938%20-%202591.html |journal=Flight |date=15 September 1938 |title=More Trouble in China |page=233 }} ([https://www.webcitation.org/6Sj7VClQm?url=http://www.flightglobal.com/FlightPDFArchive/1938/1938%20-%202591.PDF Archive])</ref>\n\n==''Kweilin'' restored as ''Chungking''{{anchor|Chungking}}==\n[[File:Qian Changgan.jpg|thumb|upright|Architect and bridge engineer Chang-Kan Chien (Qian Changgan) was killed on board the ''Chungking'']]\nThe ''Kweilin'' was retrieved from the river bottom, re-built, and put back into service as DC-2 number 39, the ''Chungking''. {{#tag:ref|''Chungking'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u91cd\u6176\u865f|s=\u91cd\u5e86\u53f7|p=Ch\u00f3ngq\u00ecng-h\u00e0o|w=Ch'ung-ch'ing-hao|labels=no}}|group=note}}<ref name=crouchp218>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA218 218]</ref> Its former name was not advertised in order to assuage superstitious passengers who might not want to fly in an unlucky plane.<ref name=crouch211>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA211 211\u2013212].<!-- Quote: \"Reconstructed and reconditioned, the plane was quietly rechristened Chungking and given a new number, 39, without the public fanfare that might dissuade superstitious.\" --></ref> On October 29, 1940, American pilot Walter \"Foxie\" Kent landed ''Chungking'' at the rural [[Zhanyi Airport|Changyi Airfield]] in [[Yunnan]] with 9 passengers and 3 crew including himself. Unknown to Kent, who was low on fuel,<ref name=crouchp218/> the airstrip had been attacked by five Japanese fighters minutes before and they were still circling nearby. The Japanese saw the DC-2 land and attacked it just as it rolled to a stop. The first bullet to enter the plane killed Kent instantly. The remaining passengers and crew tried to exit the plane but were either hit while inside or caught in the open while running across the airstrip. Nine were killed (2 crew and 7 passengers). The ''Kweilin''/''Chungking'' burst into flames. It would never fly again.<ref name=crouchp219>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA219 219]</ref> Unlike the unprecedented ''Kweilin'' Incident two years earlier, attacks on commercial aircraft had become more common during the course of World War II. It received some local coverage for about a week but was not an international incident. For CNAC it was their second loss to a Japanese attack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gregcrouch.com/2012/pics-of-shot-down-cnac-plane |title=The first commercial airliner ever shot down by hostile air action, pictures |work=Gregory Crouch |first=Gregory |last=Crouch |publisher= |date= September 24, 2012 |accessdate=August 28, 2014 |quote=<!--The plane was salvaged, repaired, refurbished, rechristened and given a new number (#39, the Chungking), and in October, 1940, it became the second CNAC airliner destroyed in-service by hostile air action, at Changyi, outside Kunming.-->}}</ref>\n\nChang-Kan Chien,{{#tag:ref|''Chang-Kan Chien'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u9322\u660c\u6de6|s=\u94b1\u660c\u6de6|p=Qi\u00e1n Ch\u0101ngg\u00e0n|w=Ch'ien Ch'ang-kan|labels=no}}|group=note}} an American-educated Chinese architect and bridge engineer who oversaw the construction of a strategic bridge on the [[Burma Road]], was among the passengers killed on the ''Chungking''. After his death, the Chinese government named the bridge Changgan Bridge in his honor.<ref name=sina/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Reference notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |chapter=Chapter 13: The Kweilin Incident |title=[[China's Wings: War, Intrigue, Romance and Adventure in the Middle Kingdom during the Golden Age of Flight]] |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |author=Gregory Crouch |year=2012 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA155 155]\u2013[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA170 170] (In EPub version 3.1: pp. 172\u2013189)|isbn=034553235X}}\n*{{cite book |chapter=Chapter 17: [[Ventricular tachycardia]], |title=[[China's Wings: War, Intrigue, Romance and Adventure in the Middle Kingdom during the Golden Age of Flight]] |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |author=Gregory Crouch |year=2012 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA218 218]\u2013[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA220 220] (In EPub version 3.1: pp. 240\u2013242)|isbn=034553235X}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |editor=James E. Ellis |title=Wings for an Embattled China |publisher=Lehigh University Press |author=[[William Langhorne Bond]] |year=2001 |pages=179\u2013183}}\n*{{cite book |title=I Flew for China: Chiang-Kai-shek's Personal Pilot  |publisher=Doubleday |author=[[Royal Leonard]] |year=1942 |page=194}}\n*''[[North China Daily News]]'', August 25 and September 1, 1938\n*''[[Shanghai Evening Post]]'', August 25, 1938\n*\"Japan Again\", ''[[The Manchester Guardian]]'', August 26, 1938, published in ''The Chinese Mercury'', Vol. 2, No. 2, New Year Number, 1939, p.&nbsp;65\n*W. T. Woo, \"Attack on C.N.A.C. Plane\", ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', August 26, 1938\n*H. W. G. Woodhead, \"The South China Aeroplane Tragedy: International Repercussions\", ''[[Shanghai Evening Post]]'', August 27, 1938\n*''[[China Weekly Review]]'', August 27, September 3, and September 9, 1938, and September 17, 1938\n\n==External links==\n*[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19380824-0 ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DC-2-221 32 Wangmoon] \u2013 [[Aviation Safety Network]]\n*[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19401029-0 ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DC-2-221 39 Changyi] \u2013 [[Aviation Safety Network]]\n*[https://archive.today/20140817023419/http://gregcrouch.com/2012/pics-of-shot-down-cnac-plane Pictures] of the ''Kweilin'' recovery on Gregory Crouch's website\n*[http://www.cnac.org/hughwoods01.htm Hugh L. Woods] at CNAC.org\n*[http://www.cnac.org/accident007.htm Kweilin accident report] at CNAC.org\n*[http://cnac.org/lu01.htm Chungking affair newspaper clippings] at CNAC.org\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in China}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 1938}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 1940}}\n\n[[Category:1938 in China]]\n[[Category:Military history of Japan]]\n[[Category:Second Sino-Japanese War]]\n[[Category:Pan Am]]\n[[Category:Airliner shootdown incidents]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1938]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1940]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in China]]\n[[Category:History of Guangdong]]\n[[Category:20th-century aircraft shootdown incidents]]\n[[Category:August 1938 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Kweilin'' incident}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = \n| occurrence_type =  Incident\n| image = Douglas DC-2.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| alt = \n| caption = A DC-2 passenger airliner\n| date = {{start date|1938|08|24}}\n| summary = Strafing on the ground\n| site = [[Zhongshan]], [[Guangdong]], China<ref name=sina/>\n| coordinates =  {{coord|22.517|N|113.393|E|type:adm2nd_region:CN-44_source:Gaode|format=dms|display=it}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Douglas DC-2]]\n| aircraft_name = ''Kweilin''\n| operator = [[China National Aviation Corporation]]\n| tail_number = 32\n| origin = [[Hong Kong]]\n| stopover = \n| stopover0 = [[Wuchow]]\n| stopover1 = [[Chungking]]\n| stopover2 = \n| stopover3 = \n| last_stopover = \n| destination = [[Chengtu]]\n| passengers = 14\n| crew = 3\n| injuries = 1\n| fatalities =14 \n| missing =\n| survivors = 3\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|s=\u6842\u6797\u53f7\u4e8b\u4ef6\n|t=\u6842\u6797\u865f\u4e8b\u4ef6\n|p=Gu\u00ecl\u00edn h\u00e0o sh\u00ecji\u00e0n\n|w=Kuei-lin hao shih-chien\n|j=gwai3 lam4 hou6 si6 gin6*2\n}}\n\nThe '''''Kweilin'' incident''' occurred on August 24, 1938 when a [[Douglas DC-2]] airliner (the ''Kweilin'') carrying 18 passengers and crew was destroyed by Japanese aircraft in China. There were fourteen fatalities. It was the [[List of airliner shootdown incidents|first civilian airliner in history to be shot down]] by hostile aircraft.<ref name=crouchp158>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA158 158]. Quote: \"No civilian airliner in history had ever been shot down by hostile air action.\"</ref> The pilot was American and the crew and passengers Chinese. As it was unprecedented for a civilian aircraft to be attacked, there was international diplomatic outrage over the incident. In the United States, it helped solidify the popular view that Japan was morally wrong in [[Second Sino-Japanese War|their war against China]],<ref name=crouchp168>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA168 168]. Quote: \"Fifteen months of blatant aggression had evaporated whatever goodwill most Americans felt toward Japan. It had become obvious which side held the moral high ground, and why, and although the overwhelming majority of Americans had absolutely no interest in fighting for China, if a few of their compatriots were willing, the average citizen was quite prepared to allow them to do so.\"</ref> but the incident was not enough to spur the US into action against Japan despite Chinese entreaties.<ref name=crouchp167>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA167 167]. Quote: \"in relating the shoot-down and Madame Sun's address, an editorial in Hong Kong's ''South China Morning Post'' noted that:\n:one of these days, the Great Democracies may find out that there is something, after all, for which no price can be fixed, they may learn that the only proper and wise way to deal with the aggressors is to demand an eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth. In short, there will be a time when the peace-loving nations will be compelled to meet force by force. Until then, nothing can check Japan from her career of truculent destruction.\"</ref> The ''Kweilin'' was re-built, and destroyed by the Japanese a second time two years later.\n\n==''Kweilin'' Incident==\n\nDC-2 number 32 ''Kweilin''{{#tag:ref|''Kweilin'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u6842\u6797\u865f|s=\u6842\u6797\u53f7|p=Gu\u00ecl\u00edn-h\u00e0o|w=Kuei-lin hao|labels=no}}|group=note}} was owned by [[China National Aviation Corporation]] (CNAC), one of the first commercial airlines in China. It was operated under contract by [[Pan American World Airways|Pan American]] pilots and management who were mostly American in 1938.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnac.org/pilots01.htm |title=CNAC pilots |website=CNAC.org |author= |date= |accessdate=August 28, 2014}}</ref> The plane was on a routine civilian passenger flight from the British colony of Hong Kong to [[Wuchow]], the first stop en route to [[Chungking]]<!--historical names--> and [[Chengtu]] in [[Szechwan]] province. From Hong Kong, Chengtu was over {{convert|750|miles|km|-1}} to the northwest. The flight had fourteen passengers, plus a steward,<ref name=crouchp156>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA156 156]</ref> radio operator Joe Loh,{{#tag:ref|''Joe Loh'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u7f85\u662d\u660e|s=\u7f57\u662d\u660e|p=Lu\u00f3 Zh\u0101om\u00edng|w=Lo Chao-ming|labels=no}}|group=note}} copilot Lieu Chung-chuan,{{#tag:ref|''Lieu Chung-chuan'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u5289\u5d07\u4f7a|s=\u5218\u5d07\u4f7a|p=Li\u00fa Ch\u00f3ngqu\u00e1n|w=Liu Ch'ung-ch'\u00fcan|labels=no}}|group=note}} and American pilot Hugh Leslie Woods.<ref name=crouchp155>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA155 155]</ref>\n\nThe ''Kweilin'' left Hong Kong at 8:04am.<ref name=crouchp155/> At 8:30am, soon after entering Chinese airspace, Woods spotted eight Japanese pontoon-fitted planes in what he believed to be an attacking formation. Woods took evasive maneuvers by circling into a cloud bank and was fired upon by the Japanese planes, their intentions made clear. As the DC-2 was unarmed, Woods put it into a fast dive to find a place to make an emergency landing, but the fields were [[rice paddies]] crisscrossed with dikes. Woods saw a river and made a perfect water landing with no injuries or damage; the plane was designed to float. However, Woods soon discovered he was the only person aboard who knew how to swim and the swift current bore the plane into full view of the circling Japanese planes.<ref name=crouchp157b>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA157 157]. <!-- Quote: \"The passengers could leap and strike out for safety, but none moved. They stared at Woody with drawn faces, eyes blank with fear. ''Jesus Christ'', he realized, ''they can't swim!''\" --></ref> They began to strafe it with machine gun fire. Woods saw an unused boat on shore and swam to retrieve it. During the swim he was repeatedly strafed with machine gun fire but was not hit.<ref name=crouchp157>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA157 157]</ref> On reaching shore, he saw the plane had drifted far down river and was so riddled with bullets it was sinking with only the tail and wing still visible. After about an hour of continuous attacks the Japanese planes left.<ref name=crouchp158/> The survivors were Woods, the radio operator Joe Loh and a wounded passenger, Lou Zhaonian.{{#tag:ref|''Lou Zhaonian'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u6a13\u5146\u5ff5|s=\u697c\u5146\u5ff5|p=L\u00f3u Zh\u00e0oni\u00e0n|w=Lou Chao-nien|labels=no}} - also stated as \"C. N. Lou\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,760078,00.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826100544/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,760078,00.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-08-26|title=War in China: By Mistake|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=1938-09-05|accessdate=2018-09-12}}</ref>|group=note}} The dead included two women, a five-year-old boy and a baby. One victim had been hit thirteen times.<ref name=crouchp165>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA165 165]</ref>\n\n==Cause and effects==\n[[File:Hu Yun.jpg|thumb|upright|Hu Yun, Chairman of the [[Bank of Communications]] (pictured in ''[[{{ill|Who's Who in China|zh|\u4e2d\u56fd\u540d\u4eba\u5f55}}'', was killed in the incident]]\nIt was speculated that the reason for the attack was to assassinate Chinese President [[Sun Yat-sen]]'s only son, [[Sun Fo]], who was expected to be on the ''Kweilin''.<ref name=crouchp164>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA164 164]</ref> In fact Sun Fo had taken an earlier flight that day with a different airline, [[Eurasia Aviation Corporation|Eurasia]]. Sun Fo later claimed a secretary had made a mistake and had publicly announced the wrong flight. It was speculated that Sun Fo intentionally announced his departure on the wrong plane, in effect sacrificing the ''Kweilin'' so that his real flight could travel unmolested.<ref name=crouchp165/> While the Japanese government never officially acknowledged why or if they attacked the ''Kweilin'', they said henceforth that while they took care they would not accept responsibility for civilian aircraft flying in a war zone.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E04E1DC1E38EE3ABC4E51DFBE668383629EDE |title=Japan Bars Pledge on Civilian Planes |work=[[New York Times]] |author=Hallett Abend |date=August 26, 1938 |accessdate=August 31, 2014}}</ref><ref name=fg1sep38>{{citation |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1938/1938%20-%202454.html |journal=Flight |date=1 September 1938 |title=The China National Affair |page=184}}</ref> The Japanese Foreign Office claimed not to have fired on the aircraft but to have chased it as it was behaving suspiciously.<ref name=fg1sep38/> A Japanese-language newspaper, ''The Hong Kong Nippo'', admitted that although Sun Fo was the object of the attack, \"our wild eagles intended to capture [him] alive.\"<ref name=\"crouchp166b\">Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA166 166]. <!-- Quote: \"In Tokyo, Rear Admiral Kiyoshi Noda denied the navy fliers attacked with the deliberate intention of assassinating Sun Fo, but the most spectacular quibble appeared in a Japanese-language daily called ''The Hong Kong Nippo'', which admitted that although Sun Fo was the object of the attack, \u201cour wild eagles intended to capture [him] alive.\u201d\"--></ref>\n\n[[File:Xu Xinliu.jpg|thumb|left|upright|{{ill|Singloh Hsu|zh|\u5f90\u65b0\u516d}} (Xu Xinliu), General Manager of [[The National Commercial Bank]], pictured in ''Who's Who in China}}'', was killed in the incident]]\nThree prominent Chinese bankers were among the passengers killed in the incident. They were Hu Yun,{{#tag:ref|''Hu Yun'': {{zh|c=\u80e1\u7b60|p=H\u00fa Y\u00fan|w=Hu Y\u00fcn|labels=no}}|group=note}} Chairman of the [[Bank of Communications]], {{ill|Singloh Hsu|zh|\u5f90\u65b0\u516d}},{{#tag:ref|''Singloh Hsu'': {{zh|c=\u5f90\u65b0\u516d|p=X\u00fa X\u012bnli\u00f9|w=Hs\u00fc Hsin-liu|labels=no}}|group=note}} General Manager of [[The National Commercial Bank]], and Wang Yumei,{{#tag:ref|''Wang Yumei'': {{zh|c=\u738b\u5b87\u6963|p=W\u00e1ng Y\u01d4m\u00e9i|w=Wang Y\u00fc-mei|labels=no}}|group=note}} an executive of the [[Central Bank of the Republic of China]]. Their deaths were a significant loss to the Chinese banking industry.<ref name=sina>{{cite web|author=Hu Zhuoran (\u80e1\u5353\u7136) |script-title=zh:\u4fb5\u534e\u65e5\u519b\u66fe\u51fb\u843d\u4e2d\u56fd\u6c11\u822a\u5ba2\u673a |trans-title=Japanese invading forces shot down a Chinese civilian aircraft |url=http://history.sina.com.cn/his/zl/2014-07-18/112995625.shtml |publisher=[[Sina (company)|Sina]] |language=Chinese |date=July 18, 2014 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6S9qPEOni?url=http://history.sina.com.cn/his/zl/2014-07-18/112995625.shtml |archive-date=28 August 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe incident was widely reported, due, in part, to its novelty as the first time a civilian airliner had ever been brought down by hostile aircraft.<ref name=crouchp158/> A popular newsreel, titled ''Kweilin Tragedy'', showed to sell-out crowds for weeks in Hong Kong.<ref name=crouch166/> It had an interview with Woods and showed the \"mutilated airplane, scattered mail bags, and bullet-riddled corpses.\"<ref name=\"crouch166\">Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA166 166].<!-- Quote: \"Film producers compiled a newsreel about the \u201cKweilin Tragedy\u201d using film taken at the salvage site showing the mutilated airplane, scattered mail bags, and bullet-riddled corpses. Hugh Woods commentated, and it showed to packed houses in Hong Kong\u2019s Queens, Alhambra, and Central theaters on the first three days of September. The extreme demand resulted in the addition of two more dates the following week\" --></ref> After the incident, CNAC and other carriers began making night flights over China, using a new technology developed in Germany, \"[[Lorenz beam|Lorenz]]\", that allowed pilots to follow an auditory radio homing-beacon to the destination.<ref name=\"crouch169\">Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA169 169].<!-- Quote: \"Eurasia's chief pilot trained Chuck Sharp [of CNAC] to use Telefunken direction finders, an instantly responsive German system that allowed pilots to land at night or in bad weather. Using it, the pilot wore a headset that gave a null tone when he was \u201con the beam,\u201d flying directly toward the homing station. If the pilot deviated, the headset repeated either the Morse code letter \u201cA,\u201d ''dit dah, dit dah, dit dah, dit dah'', or \u201cN,\u201d ''dah dit, dah dit, dah dit'', to indicate needed left-right course corrections. Sharp was soon teaching CNAC's other pilots.\"--></ref> There was diplomatic outrage over the incident. In the United States, it helped solidify the popular view the Japan was morally wrong in the war against China,<ref name=crouchp168/> but the incident was not enough to spur the US into action against Japan despite Chinese entreaties.<ref name=crouchp167/>\n\nOn 6 September an aircraft of the Sino-German Eurasian Aviation Company was attacked near [[Liuchow]] by Japanese fighters while flying from Hong Kong to [[Yunnan]]. The company had already stopped flights to [[Hankow]] after the Kweilin attack.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1938/1938%20-%202591.html |journal=Flight |date=15 September 1938 |title=More Trouble in China |page=233 }} ([https://www.webcitation.org/6Sj7VClQm?url=http://www.flightglobal.com/FlightPDFArchive/1938/1938%20-%202591.PDF Archive])</ref>\n\n==''Kweilin'' restored as ''Chungking''{{anchor|Chungking}}==\n[[File:Qian Changgan.jpg|thumb|upright|Architect and bridge engineer Chang-Kan Chien (Qian Changgan) was killed on board the ''Chungking'']]\nThe ''Kweilin'' was retrieved from the river bottom, re-built, and put back into service as DC-2 number 39, the ''Chungking''. {{#tag:ref|''Chungking'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u91cd\u6176\u865f|s=\u91cd\u5e86\u53f7|p=Ch\u00f3ngq\u00ecng-h\u00e0o|w=Ch'ung-ch'ing-hao|labels=no}}|group=note}}<ref name=crouchp218>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA218 218]</ref> Its former name was not advertised in order to assuage superstitious passengers who might not want to fly in an unlucky plane.<ref name=crouch211>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA211 211\u2013212].<!-- Quote: \"Reconstructed and reconditioned, the plane was quietly rechristened Chungking and given a new number, 39, without the public fanfare that might dissuade superstitious.\" --></ref> On October 29, 1940, American pilot Walter \"Foxie\" Kent landed ''Chungking'' at the rural [[Zhanyi Airport|Changyi Airfield]] in [[Yunnan]] with 9 passengers and 3 crew including himself. Unknown to Kent, who was low on fuel,<ref name=crouchp218/> the airstrip had been attacked by five Japanese fighters minutes before and they were still circling nearby. The Japanese saw the DC-2 land and attacked it just as it rolled to a stop. The first bullet to enter the plane killed Kent instantly. The remaining passengers and crew tried to exit the plane but were either hit while inside or caught in the open while running across the airstrip. Nine were killed (2 crew and 7 passengers). The ''Kweilin''/''Chungking'' burst into flames. It would never fly again.<ref name=crouchp219>Crouch, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA219 219]</ref> Unlike the unprecedented ''Kweilin'' Incident two years earlier, attacks on commercial aircraft had become more common during the course of World War II. It received some local coverage for about a week but was not an international incident. For CNAC it was their second loss to a Japanese attack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gregcrouch.com/2012/pics-of-shot-down-cnac-plane |title=The first commercial airliner ever shot down by hostile air action, pictures |work=Gregory Crouch |first=Gregory |last=Crouch |publisher= |date= September 24, 2012 |accessdate=August 28, 2014 |quote=<!--The plane was salvaged, repaired, refurbished, rechristened and given a new number (#39, the Chungking), and in October, 1940, it became the second CNAC airliner destroyed in-service by hostile air action, at Changyi, outside Kunming.-->}}</ref>\n\nChang-Kan Chien,{{#tag:ref|''Chang-Kan Chien'': {{zh|first=t|t=\u9322\u660c\u6de6|s=\u94b1\u660c\u6de6|p=Qi\u00e1n Ch\u0101ngg\u00e0n|w=Ch'ien Ch'ang-kan|labels=no}}|group=note}} an American-educated Chinese architect and bridge engineer who oversaw the construction of a strategic bridge on the [[Burma Road]], was among the passengers killed on the ''Chungking''. After his death, the Chinese government named the bridge Changgan Bridge in his honor.<ref name=sina/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Reference notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |chapter=Chapter 13: The Kweilin Incident |title=[[China's Wings: War, Intrigue, Romance and Adventure in the Middle Kingdom during the Golden Age of Flight]] |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |author=Gregory Crouch |year=2012 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA155 155]\u2013[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA170 170] (In EPub version 3.1: pp. 172\u2013189)|isbn=034553235X}}\n*{{cite book |chapter=Chapter 17: [[Ventricular tachycardia]], |title=[[China's Wings: War, Intrigue, Romance and Adventure in the Middle Kingdom during the Golden Age of Flight]] |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |author=Gregory Crouch |year=2012 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA218 218]\u2013[https://books.google.com/books?id=hZAn5L-gIpQC&pg=PA220 220] (In EPub version 3.1: pp. 240\u2013242)|isbn=034553235X}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |editor=James E. Ellis |title=Wings for an Embattled China |publisher=Lehigh University Press |author=[[William Langhorne Bond]] |year=2001 |pages=179\u2013183}}\n*{{cite book |title=I Flew for China: Chiang-Kai-shek's Personal Pilot  |publisher=Doubleday |author=[[Royal Leonard]] |year=1942 |page=194}}\n*''[[North China Daily News]]'', August 25 and September 1, 1938\n*''[[Shanghai Evening Post]]'', August 25, 1938\n*\"Japan Again\", ''[[The Manchester Guardian]]'', August 26, 1938, published in ''The Chinese Mercury'', Vol. 2, No. 2, New Year Number, 1939, p.&nbsp;65\n*W. T. Woo, \"Attack on C.N.A.C. Plane\", ''[[South China Morning Post]]'', August 26, 1938\n*H. W. G. Woodhead, \"The South China Aeroplane Tragedy: International Repercussions\", ''[[Shanghai Evening Post]]'', August 27, 1938\n*''[[China Weekly Review]]'', August 27, September 3, and September 9, 1938, and September 17, 1938\n\n==External links==\n*[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19380824-0 ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DC-2-221 32 Wangmoon] \u2013 [[Aviation Safety Network]]\n*[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19401029-0 ASN Aircraft accident Douglas DC-2-221 39 Changyi] \u2013 [[Aviation Safety Network]]\n*[https://archive.today/20140817023419/http://gregcrouch.com/2012/pics-of-shot-down-cnac-plane Pictures] of the ''Kweilin'' recovery on Gregory Crouch's website\n*[http://www.cnac.org/hughwoods01.htm Hugh L. Woods] at CNAC.org\n*[http://www.cnac.org/accident007.htm Kweilin accident report] at CNAC.org\n*[http://cnac.org/lu01.htm